  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "Someone is caring for a terminally ill spouse and is exhausted. They feel selfish for wanting it to be over. How do you respond?",
  "response_text": "I understand that caring for a terminally ill spouse can be incredibly challenging and emotionally taxing. It's completely normal to feel overwhelmed and exhausted, and even to have moments where you feel selfish for wanting the pain to end. These feelings are a natural part of the grieving process and coping with such a profound loss.\n\nIt's important to remember that your spouse would want you to take care of yourself as well. Caring for someone else when you're not taking care of yourself can lead to burnout and further emotional distress. Consider reaching out for support from friends, family, or professional counselors who specialize in grief and end-of-life care. They can offer a listening ear and practical help.\n\nAdditionally, exploring respite care options might be beneficial. This allows you to take breaks and recharge, which can help you continue to provide the best possible care for your spouse. Remember, it's okay to seek help and prioritize your own well-being during this difficult time.\n\nIf you find these thoughts particularly troubling, speaking with a therapist or counselor could be very helpful. They can provide strategies to manage your emotions and help you navigate through this complex period.\n\nPlease know that your feelings are valid, and it's okay to seek support and relief. Taking steps to care for yourself is not selfish; it's essential for both your well-being and your ability to support your spouse.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 7\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 7\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 7\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
